<H3> <TI>   Did Not Meet With President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Did Not Meet With President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0806150694 Taipei CNA in English 1403 GMT 8 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0806150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 8 (CNA) -- Foreign Affairs Minister 
Chien Fu disclosed Wednesday [8 June] that Premier Lien Chan did 
not meet Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari during his 
three-day stay in that country, as widely believed. Chien left 
Mexico Wednesday. 
  Chien made the remarks when answering questions by reporters 
at a farewell party for the Information &amp; Cultural Affairs 
Director Ouyang Jui-hsiung, who will take over the post of 
director-general at the Coordination Council for North American 
Affairs (CCNAA) office in Los Angeles. The CCNAA represents the 
Republic of China [ROC]'s interests in the United States in the 
absence of formal ties between the two countries. 
  Chien said he did not make public Lien's visit to Mexico 
beforehand because of an agreement between the two governments 
that neither side could release the news before Lien arrived in 
Mexico. 
  Chien said the reason he refused to comment on the 
possibility of a Salinas-Lien meet before Lien departed on his 
May 29-June 9 Central American tour was because the meeting had 
never been scheduled. Lien did meet with other ranking Mexican 
officials and Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de Leon, the ruling party's 
candidate in the next presidential election. 
  Lien, currently in New York for a two-day family reunion 
with 
his two children, who study there, will return to Taipei 
Saturday, as scheduled, and hold a press conference, Chien said. 

</TEXT>

