<H3> <TI>   Relatives To Attend `Qiandao Lake' Trial in Hangzhou </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Relatives To Attend `Qiandao Lake' Trial in Hangzhou </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706145594 Taipei CNA in English 1339 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Taipei CNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Flor Wang] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, June 7 (CNA) -- Four representatives of the 
families of the 24 Taiwan tourists killed in the March 31 
Qiandao Lake incident said Tuesday [7 June] that they will go to 
Hangzhou in southeastern Mainland China to witness the trial of 
the accused murderers, which begin this Friday. 
  [Words indistinct] said at a press conference at the 
Legislative Yuan they hope to see a fast conclusion to the 
incident [words indistinct] mainland authorities, whom they 
condemned as not having shown respect for the memories of the 
victims or concern for human rights. 
  Legislator Annette Lu, who accompanied family members of the 
24 victims at the conference, called on the entire nation to 
support them. She said she also had contacted a score of 
international human-rights organizations for support, and had 
demanded that mainland judicial authorities postpone the trial 
of the three men until facts surrounding the incident are made 
publicly known. 
  Meanwhile, H.Y. Hsu, deputy secretary-general of the Straits 
Exchange Foundation (SEF), the semi-official organization that 
handles cross-strait affairs with Mainland China in the absence 
of formal ties, called on mainland authorities not to ignore the 
rights of Taiwan citizens who lost family members in the 
incident and not to shrug off the compensation issue. 
  As facts about the Qiandao Lake incident are not entirely 
clear, he said, mainland authorities should also continue 
investigating the incident and give reasonable explanations and 
answers to questions and doubts raised about it in a report 
released by SEF and the Mainland Affairs Council. 

</TEXT>

