<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Receives Burmese Religion Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Receives Burmese Religion Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0706140094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1321 GMT 7 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0706140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, June 7 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen met here today with a Buddhist 
delegation headed by the Myanmar [Burma] minister of religious 
affairs, Lieutenant-General Myo Nyunt. 
  The delegation arrived here on June 5 to convey Buddha's 
tooth relic back to China. The sacred tooth of Buddha of China 
was allowed to be taken to Myanmar (formerly Burma) from April 
20 to June 5. 
  Qian said that the sojourn of the tooth relic in Myanmar was 
an important event in Sino-Myanmar links and religious relations 
between the two countries. 
  He expressed thanks for the careful arrangement the Myanmar 
Government had made for the sojourn. 
  Nyunt said that to make the event, a milestone of their 
bilateral relations, the Myanmar Government decided to build two 
Buddha towers in Yangon [Rangoon], its capital, and Mandalay, 
its second largest city, using donations of the Myanmar people. 
  Over 85 percent of the Myanmar population are Buddhists, and 
the country's rich cultural heritage, glittering temples and 
pagodas are well-known throughout the world. 

</TEXT>

