Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Welcomes IAEA Sanctions on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Welcomes IAEA Sanctions on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106132994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1312 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (XINHUA) -- South Korea today 
welcomed the resolution of the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA) for sanctions against the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea (DPRK) for its refusal to accept further 
inspections of its nuclear facilities. 
  A statement issued by the Foreign Ministry here said DPRK 
should learn a due lesson from the resolution and clearing up 
[as received] all its nuclear suspicions. 
  The IAEA resolution was passed by its Board of Governors in 
Vienna yesterday by a vote of 28 for, one against and four 
abstentions. 
  Under the resolution, IAEA would stop its technical 
assistance to DPRK, which amounts to 500,000-600,000 U.S. 
dollars a year. 
  In protest DPRK said that its nuclear program is peaceful 
and 
there should be "no more inspections" of its nuclear facilities 
by IAEA. 
  DPRK's envoy Yun Ho-chin told reporters in Vienna after the 
vote: "The DPRK will no longer guarantee the continuity of 
safeguards. The two IAEA inspectors still in (DPRK) will have to 
leave." 
  The envoy stressed at the closed-door meeting at the IAEA 
Vienna Headquarters that the DPRK seeks a negotiated solution to 
the crisis. 
  Just before the IAEA passed the resolution, DPRK Foreign 
Minister Kim Yong-nam said in Berlin that his country would take 
"appropriate measures" if its honor, sovereignty and security 
were endangered through sanctions. 
  The current sanctions against DPRK was the fourth of its 
kind 
imposed by IAEA on its own. South Africa, Iraq and Israel were 
the preceding countries that IAEA had punished. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

