<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Japan, U.S. Reach Accord on DPRK Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK, Japan, U.S. Reach Accord on DPRK Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1106142194 Beijing XINHUA in English 1347 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1106142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, June 11 (XINHUA) -- South Korea, the United 
States and Japan have agreed to work for phased sanctions on the 
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) over the nuclear 
standoff, the Foreign Ministry said. 
  The agreement was reached at a meeting among South Korean 
Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, visiting U.S. Under-Secretary of 
State for Political Affairs Peter Tarnoff and Japanese Foreign 
Minister Koji Kakizawa here today. 
  The three diplomats said that sanctions against Pyongyang 
were inevitable now since the opportunity for measurements from 
DPRK's 5-megawatt nuclear reactor is damaged, ministry spokesman 
Chang Ki-ho said. 
  Earlier, the DPRK refuted the allegation that the 
measurements had become impossible, saying discharging fuel rods 
at the reactor was always under IAEA camera screening. 
  The three sides agreed that close Seoul-Washington-Tokyo 
cooperation is necessary in dealing with DPRK's nuclear issue, 
the spokesman said. 
  However, there was no report on any statement by Tarnoff and 
Kakizawa themselves after the meeting. 
  The spokesman quoted Kakizawa as saying that Japan will take 
responsible actions "within the limits of the Japanese 
Constitution" when the U.N. Security Council decides to act. 
  Tarnoff and Kakizawa arrived here over the weekend for key 
talks with South Korean officials on the nuclear controversy. 
  Strongly opposing sanctions, DPRK has stated that its 
nuclear 
program is peaceful. It warned that imposition of sanctions 
will be an act of war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

