<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Meets Kakizawa, Urges `Dialogue' on DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Meets Kakizawa, Urges `Dialogue' on DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1206093794 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0808 
GMT 12 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1206093794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 12 Jun (XINHUA) -- Qian Qichen, State 
Council vice premier and foreign minister, met today at the 
Diaoyutai State Guesthouse with Japanese Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa, who is now on a working visit to China. Qian Qichen 
and Kakizawa exchanged views on bilateral relations and on the 
issue of the Korean peninsula's nuclear problem. 
  Foreign Minister Kakizawa briefed Qian Qichen on Japan's 
views concerning the current situation. 
  Qian Qichen pointed out concerning the Korean peninsula's 
nuclear issue that the Chinese Government has always persisted 
in the basic goals of promoting a nuclear-free Korean peninsula 
and of maintaining peace and stability on the peninsula. 
Because these two goals are in accord with the fundamental 
interests of all the countries of Northeast Asia, they should 
become the basic starting point for seeking a proper solution to 
the current problem. 
  Qian Qichen pointed out that China is greatly concerned 
about 
the serious difficulties surrounding the Korean peninsula's 
nuclear issue. We regret the action taken by the International 
Atomic Energy Agency on 10 June to temporarily halt technical 
assistance to [North] Korea and the consequences resulting from 
that action. When faced with difficulties, it is particularly 
necessary for the parties concerned to maintain calm and to 
exercise restraint, not to simply close the door to dialogue, 
and to do everything possible to leave room to maneuver and to 
maintain the possibility of solving this problem through 
dialogue. Sanctions will not help to solve problems and can 
only sharpen contradictions and might lead to consequences that 
no one wants to see. We call on the parties concerned to try 
their best to start up the dialogue, to alleviate the 
contradictions, and to seek ways for a proper solution to the 
problem. 

</TEXT>

