<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Bonds `Pillar' of National Securities Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Bonds `Pillar' of National Securities Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1306092294 Beijing XINHUA in English 0743 GMT 13 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1306092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, June 13 (XINHUA) -- The issuing of state 
bonds has become a pillar of China's securities market alongside 
the listed stocks, after six years of effort. 
  China has issued six types of such bonds since 1981. The 
amount expanded from 19.8 billion yuan-worth in 1981 to 100 
billion yuan-worth this year. 
  Until 1988 state bonds were not allowed to be put onto the 
market, a local bank official said. 
  "Although the interest rate on the bonds was higher than on 
the bank's savings deposits, people still regarded their 
purchase as making a contribution to the state and not making an 
investment for themselves," he explained. 
  A survey shows that the transactional volume of the Shanghai 
market for state bonds amounted to 11.321 billion yuan-worth in 
five trading days from May 30 to June 3, while that of stocks on 
the Shanghai Stock Exchange during this period reached only 2.54 
billion yuan-worth. 
  According to the official, state bond futures are more 
attractive to investors. 
  At present, China is working out a package of regulations to 
ensure the healthy development of these markets. 

</TEXT>

